1. Ratification of First Amendments to the 2018-19 Operations Agreements for Health Sciences Middle School and Health Sciences High School
Meeting
Feb 5, 2019 - Regular Charter Meeting, 6:00 P.M.
Type
Action

RECOMMENDATION: Ratify the First Amendments to the 2018-19 Operations Agreements for Health Sciences Middle School and Health Sciences High School/Health Sciences High School and Middle College.  The lease term is January 16, 2019 to January 15, 2039.

 

FISCAL IMPACT: None.

 

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT: None.

 

IMPACT TO DISTRICT STAFFING: None.

 

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: Not applicable.

 

BACKGROUND: These First Amendments are necessary to formalize the change in the District’s supervisorial oversight fee from 1 percent to 3 percent, effective February 1, 2019, for Health Science Middle School and Health Science High School's occupancy of District-owned facilities. On or about January 8, 2019, Health Science High School and Middle College, as tenant, and the District, as landlord/owner, entered into a long term lease for 3910 University Avenue, San Diego, 92102, and 3995 Polk Avenue, San Diego, 92102, for $120 per year, prepaid annually, for the beneficial occupancy of Health Science Middle and Health Science High. Under Education Code section 47613, the District may charge for the actual costs of supervisorial oversight of a charter school not to exceed 3 percent of the revenue of the charter school if the charter school is able to obtain substantially rent free facilities from the chartering authority, as in this case. The 20-year lease commences January 16, 2019.

RENEWAL VERSUS REVISION

 

A petition to open a new charter school can be approved by the district for up to a five-year term. Near the end of the term, a charter school applies for “renewal” of its charter to continue operating for another five-year term. Education Code section 47605 requires the review and approval process for new and renewing charter petitions to take place over two board meetings: (i) public hearing, and (ii) action to grant/deny.

 

Within a five-year term, a charter school may request the district’s approval to revise its existing charter pursuant to Education Code section 47607. Proposed revisions may include a change in the school’s location, reassignment of special education responsibilities, expansion of grade levels, or other significant change.

In addition to the above required modifications, the following clarification to the charter is necessary:

  1. Clarification to page 91 regarding Governance (KIPP requested this change).

The KIPP SoCal Schools Board of Directors is comprised of community members. The authorized number of directors on the KIPP SoCal Schools Board shall not be less than three (3) and not greater than twenty (20). Board members can serve up to three, three-year terms (nine years total). The Board is comprised of individuals with experience in education, nonprofits, entrepreneurial growth companies, legal, real estate, community service, philanthropy, media, and education policy. KIPP SoCal Public Schools seeks to have a diverse board that can provide a variety of expertise, opinions, and perspectives to help the organization continue to improve.

 

FISCAL IMPACT: None. 

 

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT: None. 

 

IMPACT TO DISTRICT STAFFING: None. 

 

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: Not applicable.

 

BACKGROUND: KIPP Adelante Preparatory Academy (“KIPP”), is a charter school serving Grades 5-8 at 1475 6th Avenue (92101). KIPP is currently operated by KIPP San Diego, a nonprofit public benefit corporation, pursuant to Education Code 47604. KIPP San Diego seeks to merge into KIPP LA Schools, and the KIPP LA Schools nonprofit corporation will become KIPP SoCal. As of July 1, 2019, KIPP SoCal will operate the KIPP Adelante. Operating under the larger KIPP SoCal corporation will allow KIPP to receive additional supports and benefits from the corporation, with the anticipated result being an increase in student academic performance at the site.

 

The KIPP SoCal Board of Directors is to be comprised of at least three and no more than twenty board members. Members serve three-year terms. There are currently 13 members on the KIPP SoCal board. A minimum of one current KIPP San Diego member will be appointed to the KIPP SoCal board. The board intends to meet at least four times per year.

 

The current KIPP San Diego board members will become the San Diego Community Advisory Council. The Advisory Council’s role will be to promote the KIPP operations, provide local perspective and input to inform the KIPP SoCal board, advocate in the San Diego community, and review KIPP’s performance and budget.

 

KIPP LA Schools currently operates 17 schools serving 7,300 students in Los Angeles County, and KIPP San Diego operates one school in San Diego serving 327 students. Based on the percentage of schools and students in San Diego versus Los Angeles, KIPP SoCal intends to hold only one board meeting every two years in San Diego. Staff is concerned that one meeting every two years in San Diego is not fulfilling a commitment to local control and local accountability.

 

The following map identifies the locations of the 17 schools that KIPP operates in Los Angeles County. The black circle is a radius of approximately 7.6 miles.

 

 

1. KIPP Empower Academy

2. KIPP Ignite Academy

3. KIPP Iluminar Academy

4. KIPP Promesa Prep.

5. KIPP Raíces Academy

6. KIPP Vida Academy

7. KIPP Comienza Community Prep.

8. KIPP Comienza Community Prep.

9. KIPP Comienza Community Prep.

10. KIPP Corazón Academy

11. KIPP Compton Community School

12. KIPP Academy of Innovation

13. KIPP Academy of Opportunity

14. KIPP LA Prep.

15. KIPP Scholar Academy

16. KIPP Sol Academy

17. KIPP Philosophers Academy

18. KIPP LA Schools Office

 

According to the map, all 17 of the schools are within 16 miles of each other, and several of the schools are clustered near each other. In reviewing the 2017-18 board meeting agendas, it appears that several of the meetings were held at the KIPP LA Schools Office (#18 on the map). The geographic locations of these schools makes it easier for families enrolled at these sites to participate at board meetings in person, regardless of which of the 18 sites the meeting is held at.

 

San Diego is approximately 115 miles away from the KIPP LA Schools Office and the geographically closest KIPP LA school. If the majority of meetings are held this far away, it makes it difficult for San Diego families to attend a meeting in person.

 

Staff is recommending that at least one KIPP SoCal board meeting be held in San Diego each school year. This will provide San Diego families the opportunity to participate in the meetings in person, and supports the goals of local control and local accountability.

 

As of August 2019, KIPP intends to relocate from its current site in downtown San Diego to a new site in the Encanto area, located at 326 Euclid Avenue, 92114. This new facility will allow KIPP to increase its enrollment, and have students occupy a site which will look more like a school site than an office building.

  1. Charter Revision Form (December 11, 2018).
  2. Charter Facility Confirmation Form (January 11, 2019)
  3. Resolution and Approval of Merger (October 8, 2018)
  4. KIPP SoCal Articles of Incorporation (November 2, 2018)
  5. KIPP SoCal Amended Bylaws (November 2, 2018)
  6. KIPP San Diego Agendas and Minutes (October 8, 2018 and December 10, 2018)

Analysis Based on KIPP’s Projected Enrollment

Using KIPP’s proposed enrollment, the LCFF revenues presented are within range of district staff’s calculations. Budgeted expenditures show an overall decrease in expenses from prior years due to the “merger” with KIPP LA and sharing the costs of multiple expenses. The expenditures are reasonable and account for an increase in cost of living; however, they do not appear to account for the growth in enrollment for 2020-21 and 2021-22. District staff adjusted expenditures to reflect the growth in enrollment. KIPP projects operational surpluses each year with ending fund balances that meet the district’s reserve requirement of the greater of 3 percent of expenditures or $50,000. The following table summarizes the ending fund balances.

Analysis Based on No Growth in Enrollment

Using the conservative enrollment, district staff adjusted the budget for overstated revenues and expenditures, resulting in a decrease in net assets of $24,385 in fiscal year 2019-20 and increases in nets assets of $65,151 and $73,556 in fiscal years 2020-21 and 2021-22, respectively. KIPP’s ending fund balance meets the district’s minimum reserve requirement in each year. The following table summarizes the ending fund balances.

CONCLUSION

 

Staff recommends approval, with the required modifications, of the following revisions to the charter of KIPP Adelante Preparatory Academy, effective July 1, 2019:

    1. Change the Governance structure of the charter.
    2. Change the name of the nonprofit public benefit corporation that operates the charter school to “KIPP SoCal,” as well as the Bylaws, Articles of Incorporation, and Conflict of Interest Code.
    3. Add a new location.

[Originator/Contact: Deidre Walsh, Manager, Office of Charter Schools, Office of the Operations Support Officer, 619.725.7107, dwalsh@sandi.net]
